0.05244352,0.00744096,0.06132453,-0.03933609,0.01924130,0.03512868,0.08147554,-0.01121052,-0.00308614,0.06148249,-0.01027876,0.02454754,-0.05413302,0.01446535,0.02515078,0.00890360,-0.05321966,-0.05162589,0.01865743,0.03673896,0.02038070,0.05831208,-0.02257657,-0.05020179,-0.11257904,0.05848277,-0.06073959,0.02962983,-0.03160549,0.03534056,0.05861940,-0.03695198,0.00991309,0.03999488,-0.00460450,-0.05248532,-0.01009286,0.02662928,-0.03584328,0.04705437,-0.05500291,0.01929515]',E'Using Port Forwarding\n\nKubernetes port forwarding creates a redirection from your local machine to use a MySQL client, such as `mysql` or MySQL Workbench. \nFor example, for read-write connection to the primary using the MySQL protocol:\n\n```sh\n$> kubectl port-forward service/mycluster mysql\n\nForwarding from 127.0.0.1:3306 -> 6446\nForwarding from [::1]:3306 -> 6446\n```\n\nAnd in a second terminal:\n\n```sh\n$> mysql -h127.0.0.1 -P3306 -uroot -p\n\nEnter password:\nWelcome to the MySQL monitor.  Commands end with ; or \\g.\n...\n```\n\nWhen prompted, enter the password used when creating the Secret.','{"source": "mysql", "version": "9.0", "language": "sql", "title": "MySQL Operator for Kubernetes", "section_title": "README", "url": "https://github.com/mysql/mysql-operator/blob/trunk/README.md", "topics": "mysql/operator,README", "categories": "database,sql,relational,kubernetes,operator"}');
